article.description:
Shereka Wright had 26 points, and
seventh-ranked Purdue avoided a second straight road loss to open
the Big Ten Conference season, escaping with a 59-53 victory
Thursday night over Wisconsin.
article.headline: Wright scores 26 points for Boilermakers
article.linkText: Wright way helps No. 7 Purdue escape Wisconsin
article.story:
MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Two-time defending Big Ten Conference
champion Purdue hasn't lost its first two games in league play for
17 seasons. That streak appeared in jeopardy Thursday night, but the
Boilermakers hung on to beat Wisconsin, which was tied with No. 7
Purdue with just 3:58 remaining.

	   But then Shereka Wright stopped the upset bid in its tracks. The
All-American forward knocked down a tiebreaking jumper from the
wing, and later sank a pair of key free throws with 43.1 seconds
left for the last of her 26 points to propel Purdue to a 59-53
victory.

	   "I think we understood the sense of urgency, finally,"
Boilermakers coach Kristy Curry said. "We're going to have to get
(that) fixed or I'm going to have a different starting lineup. I'm
not trying to threaten them. I think they'll get it going."

	   With senior forward Kristi Seeger available only in spurts while
nursing the start of a stress fracture in her lower left leg, and
senior guard Leah Hefte on the bench in the second half after
aggravating a shoulder injury, Wisconsin was left with essentially
a seven-player rotation and few options to defend Wright.

	   Ebba Gebisa -- whose father is a professor at Purdue -- was left
with primary responsibility and was unable to contain Wright at
crucial times. She sank 9-of-14 shots from the field and went
9-of-11 at the free-throw line.

	   "She really was just a little too much for us," Badgers coach
Jane Albright said of Wright, who also had nine rebounds.

	   Emily Heikes added 12 points and Mary Jo Noon 10 for the
Boilermakers (12-2, 1-1 ), who rebounded from a 67-62 loss Monday
at Michigan State.

	   Emily Ashbaugh had a career-high 19 points and a team-best three
assists for Wisconsin (2-10, 0-2), which has beaten only
Texas-Arlington and Eastern Illinois and is off to the worst
12-game start in school history.

	   Albright said coming so close to a win against the
seventh-ranked team should give her players confidence.

	   "My heart hurts for them, because they put so much into it and
wanted to win so badly," Albright said.

	   The Boilermakers were held scoreless for the first 5:18 until
Heikes ended the drought with a free throw.

	   "I guess you could say it was a shock, in a way," Heikes said
of the horrid start. "I don't think we really came out to play
like we were expected to."

	   Ashbaugh kept Wisconsin rolling with 10 points in the first
eight minutes. But when Ashley Josephson picked up her second foul
midway through the half, Wisconsin was left without a true point
guard to bring the ball up the court and the Boilermakers' press
paid dividends.

	   Purdue forced turnovers on seven of the Badgers' next 11
possessions, fueling a 9-0 run to tie the game at 18-18 with 5:57
left in the half. Wright had 11 of the Boilermakers' first 18
points.

	   The second half was tightly contested throughout. There were
seven lead changes and seven ties in the first 17 minutes, with
Purdue leading by no more than two points and Wisconsin by three.

	   Back-to-back baskets by Wright and Erika Valek from the wings
gave Purdue a 54-50 advantage with 2:51 remaining. Ashbaugh made
the front end of a bonus with 1:23 left to trim the gap to three
points and then stymied Wright on a drive, but lost the ball out of
bounds.

	   The Boilermakers shaved 22 seconds off the shot clock before
Wright drew a shooting foul on Ashbaugh and hit both free throws,
making it 58-53 Purdue with 43.1 seconds left.

	   The Badgers shot 47.6 percent from the field but hurt their
cause with 22 turnovers. Purdue went 15-of-20 from the line.
